    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-08-19T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-08-19T08:00:00-05:00" n="465"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d465">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 868.51 War Credits /4</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_DG1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Droppers</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-08-19T15:00:00+02:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 19, 1917, 3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 9.45 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>391. Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_VEK1">Venizelos</persName> called upon
                    me yesterday and stated that he was anxious to mobilize as soon as possible
                    against Central powers but lacked the means. Previous Ministries had left empty
                    treasury. England and France would advance civil law [<hi rend="italic"
                        >loan</hi>] to Greece. Would the American Government come to his assistance
                    with a military loan? After promising to telegraph his request I stated that
                    this question in my opinion could be settled in cooperation with England and
                    France to which statement he cordially agreed. Military support of Greece may be
                    in time of great importance.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Droppers</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
